ction, How to Be a Friend explores how to choose the right friends, how to avoid the pitfalls of friendship, and how to live with friends in good times and bad. Cicero also praises what he sees as the deepest kind of friendship—one in which two people find in each other “another self” or a kindred soul.An honest and eloquent guide to finding and treasuring true friends, How to Be a Friend speaks as powerfully today as when it was first written.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aConduct of lifexPhilosophyxEarly works to 1800. 0aFriendshipxEarly works to 1800. 0aFriendshipxPhilosophy. 0aFriendship. 0aPhilosophyxEarly works to 1800. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  a133 BC.  a141 BC.  a146 BC.  a168 BC.  a194 BC.  a202 BC.  a218 BC.  a280 BC.  a509 BC.  a88 BC.  aAchilles and Patroclus.  aAdornment.  aAffair.  aAfter Virtue.  aAgrarian law.  aBasic goodness.  aBattle of Zama.  aBias of Priene.  aCalculation.  aCato the Elder.  aChild of God.  aChilon of Sparta.  aCicero.  aClothing.  aCognomen.  aCourtesy.  aDe Legibus.  aDe re publica.  aDeed.  aDemagogue.  aDictatorship.  aDisadvantage.  aEmpedocles.  aEnnius.  aEnthusiasm.  aEveryday life.  aFaithfulness.  aFlattery.  aGaius Gracchus.  aGaius Laelius.  aGenerosity.  aGreeks.  aHannibal.  aHarmony with nature.  aIntellectual.  aKing of Rome.  aLaelius de Amicitia.  aManius Curius Dentatus.  aMarcus Porcius Cato (son of Cato the Younger).  aModernity.  aMonarchy.  aMoral character.  aMourning.  aMyson of Chenae.  aNatural kind.  aNickname.  aNumantia.  aOrator.  aOxford University Press.  aPacuvius.  aPhilosopher.  aPirithous.  aPittacus of Mytilene.  aPlaywright.  aPlebs.  aPontifex Maximus.  a